Topic
GKE Workload Identity — end-to-end rebuild from memory

Objective
Rebuild the full Workload Identity chain without prompting:
cluster → GSA → KSA → binding → annotation → proof via logs

Key Concepts
- KSA (Kubernetes Service Account) lives in the cluster; created with kubectl
- GSA (GCP Service Account) lives in IAM; created with gcloud
- Workload Identity bridges the two — no key files needed
- Binding grants the KSA permission to impersonate the GSA
- Annotation tells the KSA which GSA to impersonate
- Proof: kubectl logs shows GSA email as the active authenticated account
- --workload-pool must be set at cluster creation — cannot be added after

Practical Work Completed
- Created GKE cluster with --workload-pool flag
- Created GSA (gsa-sa) via gcloud
- Created KSA (ksa-sa) via kubectl
- Bound KSA to GSA with roles/iam.workloadIdentityUser
- Annotated KSA with GSA email
- Deployed test pod running google/cloud-sdk:slim as KSA
- Confirmed GSA email appeared in kubectl logs — chain proven
- Cleaned up: pod, cluster, GSA deleted cleanly

Confusions / Fixes
- --serviceaccount flag removed in newer kubectl — used --overrides instead
- Chat interface mangled URLs into hyperlinks — commands still worked

Mental Model
Pod → KSA → GSA → GCP APIs
